arch:property.oc:show_val: Soil above the “hypocaust room” floor (Locus 42) covered by the raised floor (Locus 102)

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
3.07 m north south -by- 0.84 m east west.

Locus 109 is the soil above the “hypocaust room” floor (Locus 42) covered by the raised floor (Locus 102) in the west of the room. The locus was not excavated, as the floor covering it was left intact. From what is now visible, it is possible to say that there may be some leveling stones underneath the floor in this locus, though this is really not clear. The soil is a fine loose sand that balls and has a Munsell of 7.5 YR 3/3 (dark brown). Inclusions of small stones and pottery are also visible. Nothing more can be said without removing some of the pavers of Locus 102 and excavating the locus. Most likely, the locus is quite similar to Locus 9, the brown soil just above the floor of the “hypocaust room.” Because of its position underneath Locus 102, and its possible function to level that floor, Locus 109 is tentatively assigned to Stage 4.
